│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure inside            │
│ BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands asserting that an instruction being    │
│ erased has no live users or that all its users are already marked deleted. In │
│ the provided reproducer, the SLP vectorizer's horizontal-reduction path marks │
│ a set of scalar instructions for deletion, but some of their users (like      │
│ logical and/select chains participating in the reduction) remain live and are │
│ not marked deleted. When removeInstructionsAndOperands drops operands and     │
│ proceeds to remove the instructions from their parent, the assertion triggers │
│ because there are still users that are not recognized as deleted.\n\n2.       │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug-only log shows SLP vectorization forming      │
│ bundles for compares and zexts and deciding to vectorize them. Then it        │
│ collects scalars to remove (RemovedInsts): zexts, compares, and the repeated  │
│ tobools. It validates users with the condition that each user is either       │
│ inside the SLP tree, in the UserIgnoreList, or already deleted. This is a     │
│ diagnostic assertion only. After vectorization, for reduction-specific        │
│ handling, the code replaces uses of some instructions with poison for users   │
│ in UserIgnoreList. However, the conditions to do replacement are selective    │
│ (depend on IE->Idx and other properties). As a result, some users (e.g.,      │
│ logical and/select forming the reduction chain: %2, %4, %7, %5, %8, %11, %12) │
│ still reference the scalars scheduled for deletion and are not marked as      │
│ deleted, which violates the removal-time assertion.\nThe log confirms the     │
│ first transformation point is removeInstructionsAndOperands, and the crash    │
│ occurs right at the assertion that checks users of the to-be-erased           │
│ instructions.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nremoveInstructionsAndOperands       │
│ assumes that every instruction passed in DeadVals either has no users or all  │
│ its users have already been marked with DeletedInstructions. This assumption  │
│ is violated in the horizontal reduction path where RemovedInsts collects      │
│ scalars, but their users are not consistently marked deleted unless they are  │
│ vectorized tree nodes or explicitly in the UserIgnoreList and had their uses  │
│ replaced. In this case, some users are neither deleted nor replaced before we │
│ attempt to remove the scalars, triggering the assertion.\nThis mismatch is    │
│ specific to the reduction handling: RemovedInsts may include operands (like   │
│ compares and zexts) used by reduction-chain instructions that are not in      │
│ RemovedInsts and not yet marked deleted.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nWe   │
│ need to make removeInstructionsAndOperands resilient to internal reduction    │
│ users that are tracked in UserIgnoreList but not yet deleted at this point.   │
│ Two options exist:\n- Eagerly mark users in UserIgnoreList as deleted prior   │
│ to the assertion.\n- Loosen the assertion to treat UserIgnoreList-contained   │
│ users as logically deleted, since the reduction machinery plans to clean them │
│ up later.\nA minimal change that preserves existing invariants is to extend   │
│ the check to accept users in the UserIgnoreList and also pre-mark such        │
│ instruction users as deleted to keep internal bookkeeping consistent. Insert  │
│ the following logic just before the assertion in                              │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands:\n\nAt lines 2744-2756 in                       │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, add handling to pre-mark     │
│ users that are in UserIgnoreList as deleted and extend the assertion to allow │
│ them:\n\n--- begin edit ---\nfor (T *V : DeadVals) {\n  auto *I =             │
│ cast<Instruction>(V);\n  if (!I->getParent())\n    continue;\n  // If some    │
│ users are in the ignore list (e.g. during horizontal reduction),\n  // mark   │
│ them as deleted so the assertion below treats them as internal users.\n  if   │
│ (!I->use_empty() && UserIgnoreList) {\n    for (Use &U : I->uses()) {\n       │
